    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 2nd with a focus on speed-leveraging and platoon efficiency. The clear offensive anchor today is **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (75.89), whose favorable matchup against R. Nelson yields a elite-tier score bolstered by significant dynamic platoon advantages. Following closely are **Colt Keith** (65.83) and **Junior Caminero** (64.04). **Colt Keith** benefits immensely from the high-upside matchup against Kumar Rocker, where the combination of the starter's slow delivery\u2014a prime opportunity for our aggressive baserunning strategy\u2014and the favorable platoon split makes him a top-tier start. **Caleb Durbin** remains an essential, albeit low-order, play; while his #9 spot carries an 8% penalty, his 19% boost derived from the SP's skill profile and the team\u2019s emphasis on stolen base potential keeps him squarely in the 62.04 range, confirming his utility despite the lack of lineup protection.\n\nRisks today are concentrated in our premium assets facing difficult arms. **Yordan Alvarez** (51.14) faces a stiff test against Early, with his score suppressed by a brutal 19% penalty against the SP's skill set and an unfavorable same-handed matchup. Similarly, **Trea Turner** (58.91) and **Kyle Schwarber** (55.94) are slightly hindered by the matchup against Meyer, though **Trea Turner** maintains startable status thanks to his premium leadoff role. On the bench, **Chase Meidroth** (44.21) was the final man out; while his profile was respectable, the optimizer opted for **Josh Smith** in the starting lineup because of the latter\u2019s massive 14% dynamic platoon advantage against K. Montero. We continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains sidelined, and have verified that **Zac Veen** is still down in Albuquerque, meaning we must rely on our active depth to navigate these pending lineups for **Hyeseong Kim**, **Luke Raley**, and **Josh Smith**.",
